			<h3 ><a href="#p1740088">Re: Cheap Razors</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1740088&amp;sid=e801c7446165e76c4134a839dcb712e1#p1740088"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=34652&amp;sid=e801c7446165e76c4134a839dcb712e1">windaar</a></strong> &raquo; Wed Jul 03, 2013 7:54 am </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>kwan2 wrote:</cite>er whatsa DE, how to map a beard? and what about my question on switching back and forth ?</div></blockquote><br /><br />DE = Double Edged blade, the kind your Dad used. Razor for these would be an old Gillette safety razor found on eBay or a brand new model such as a Merkur. I prefer an old Gillette. One in good condition will last forever they are made of nickel coated brass and they are well constructed. Blades are plentiful through many online sources such as Amazon. WalMart does carry Wilkinsons in a 10-pack for less than $2.  You &quot;map&quot; your beard by figuring out the way the grain changes across your face and neck, and then shave accordingly, as described in the above posts. I don't know about switching from blade to electric. I avoid electrics entirely since they really ravage one's skin.</div>

			

		</div>

		
